t later came to denote one who looked after the churchyard and dug graves.","English: in northern England a variant of   Saxton  .","English: possibly a habitational name from Sexton in Ermington (Devon), recorded as <i>Shecoteston</i> in 1329. The placename derives from the family of Richard <i>Sheccoc</i>, recorded at Sexton in 1199, + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘farmstead, village, settlement’. The origin of Richard <i>Sheccoc</i>'s name is uncertain due to confusion between <i>c</i> and <i>t</i>, as seen in the name of one of his descendants, Richard <i>Scheccote</i>, recorded at Sexton in 1333."],"variants":[{"name":"Sexson","meanings":["Probably a variant of   Sexton  ."]},{"name":"Saxton","meanings":["English: habitational name principally from Saxton (Yorkshire), but perhaps occasionally from the lost Saxton preserved in Saxon Street in Woodditton (Cambridgeshire). The Yorkshire placename probably derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Saxi</i> (see   Sax   3) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though the first element may alternatively be Old English <i>Seaxe</i> ‘the Saxons’ (in the stem-form <i>Seax-</i>) or perhaps Old English <i>seax</i> ‘stone, rock’. The Cambridgeshire placename probably derives from Old English <i>Seaxe</i> (in the stem-form <i>Seax-</i>) + <i>tūn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Rose Alice Sexton was born in 1161, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert Sexton. She had at least 1 son with Robert Gurdon. She died in 1220, in her hometown, at the age of 59, and was buried in Rhynie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1161–1220":"1161–1220","1157–1240":"1157–1240","1194–1251":"1194–1251","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1157":"1157","1220":"1220","1251":"1251","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1161":"1161","1194":"1194","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scudarque, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Rhynie, , Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Rhynie, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1161–1220":"1161–1220","1157–1240":"1157–1240","1194–1251":"1194–1251","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1157":"1157","1220":"1220","1251":"1251","1240":"